from wagner david wagner subject re deuterocanonical esp sirach larry larry l overacker shellgate llo write i not dave davi write the deutero-canonical book be add much later in the church history they do not have the same spiritual quality a the rest of scripture i do not believe the church that add these book wa guide by the spirit in so do and that be where thi sort of discussion ultimately end sorry i put my foot in my mouth concern the church history it be correct to say that the council of hippo list the deuterocanonical book among those accept for use in the church and that thi wa ratify by the council of carthage and by pope innoent i and gelasiu i ad yet eerdman history of the church say at the end of the fourth century view still differ in regard to the extent of the canon or the number of the book which should be acknowledge a divine and authoritative the jewish canon or the hebrew bible wa universally receive while the apocrypha add to the greek version of the septuagint be only in a general way account a book suitable for church read and thu a a middle clas between canonical and strictly apocryphal pseudonymou write and justly for those book while they have great historical value and fill the gap between the old testament and the new all originate after the cessation of prophecy and the can not be therefore regard a inspire nor be they ever cite by christ or the apostele in the western church the canon of both testament wa close at the end of the fourth century through the authority of jerome who waver however between critical doubt and the principle of tradition and more especially of augustine who firmly follow the alexandrian canon of the septuagint and the preponderant tradition in reference to the catholic epistle and the revelation though he himself in some place incline to consider the old testament apocrypha a deutero canonical bear a subordinate authority thi history go on to say that augustine attend both the council of hippo and of carthage it be interest to note however the follow footnote to the fourth session of the council of trent the footnote list variou synod which endorse list of canonical book but then say the tridentine list or decree wa the first infallible and effectually promulgate declaration on the canon of the holy scripture which lead one to think that the rc canon wa not official until trent thu my previou erroneou statement wa not entirely groundles it be also interest to note that the council of trent go on to uphold the old latin vulgate edition of the scripture a authentic which i would suppose today catholic scholar wish the council have never say also the council make no distinction between deutero-canonical and canonical book in contrast to eerdman statement of the fourth century view david wagner a confessional lutheran 